$ Powershell command noun: content

The command noun `content` deals with the *content* of → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/item[items].

Commands related to the → Windows/PowerShell[PowerShell] command noun `content`:
  • `add-content`
  • `clear-content`
  • → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/content/get[`get-content`]
  • → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/content/set[`set-content`]

{ Inplace editing #ps-inplace-editing

  A combination of `get-content`, `set-content` and the → Windows/PowerShell/language/operator/string-manipulation#ps-replace[`-replace`] string → Windows/PowerShell/language/operator[operator] allows to
  edit a file *in place* (much as might be done in → Linux with → development/languages/sed/in-place-editing[`sed -i`]).

  The following (simple) → Windows/PowerShell/pipeline modifies `some.text`: it replaces `#text#` with `"Hello world"` and `#num#` with `42`.

  gh|about-PowerShell|/cmdlets/content/inplace-editing.ps1||

  Thus
  gh|about-PowerShell|/cmdlets/content/some.text.orig||
  becomes
code {
The text is "Hello World" and the
number is 42.
code }

}

sa:
  → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun
